let d_cc42d100ec0f9356086a8bc331da284c = " few directories and files to it.</p>\n\n<div class=\"highlight\"><pre><code class=\"language-bash\" data-lang=\"bash\"><span class=\"nv\">$ </span>mount /dev/xvda /media/\n<span class=\"nv\">$ </span><span class=\"nb\">cd</span> /media/ \n<span class=\"nv\">$ </span>mkdir -p boot/grub</code></pre></div>\n\n<p>After making the boot and grub directories on /dev/xvda, we can then create the boot/grub/menu.lst file. It should contain text similar to the following (NOTE: your mirage kernel may not have the same name but should generally end with .xen). You\226\128\153ll need to use nano or cat fu for this as that\226\128\153s what is installed on Finnix. You could also rsync this file over using similar instructions to getting the kernel on the server. </p>\n\n<div class=\"highlight\"><pre><code class=\"language-bash\" data-lang=\"bash\"><span class=\"nv\">$ </span>cat &gt; /media/boot/grub/menu.lst <span class=\"s\">&lt;&lt; EOF</span>\n<span class=\"s\">&gt; timeout 1</span>\n<span class=\"s\">&gt;</span>\n<span class=\"s\">&gt; title Mirage</span>\n<span class=\"s\">&gt; root (hd0)</span>\n<span class=\"s\">&gt; kernel /boot/mir-www.xen root=/dev/xvda ro quiet</span>\n<span class=\"s\">&gt; EOF</span></code></pre></div>\n\n<p>After this is done we\226\128\153ll need to set up a root password and start ssh so we can get the Mirage kernel onto the Linode. </p>\n\n<div class=\"highlight\"><pre><code class=\"language-bash\" data-lang=\"bash\"><span class=\"nv\">$ </span>passwd\nEnter new UNIX password: \nRetype new UNIX password: \npasswd: password updated successfully \n<span class=\"nv\">$ </span>service ssh start</code></pre></div>\n\n<p>Once ssh has started we can then rsync the kernel over ssh from our local work station. </p>\n\n<div class=\"highlight\"><pre><code class=\"language-bash\" data-lang=\"bash\"><span class=\"nv\">$ </span>rsync -avPz mir-www.xen root@ip.address.ofyour.linode:/media/boot/</code></pre></div>\n\n<h3 id=\"its-alive\">It\226\128\153s Alive!</h3>\n\n<p>After this is complete, go back to your Linode Dashboard (under the dashboard tab) and click <code>Reboot</code>. If all goes well you should be able to navigate to your Linode\226\128\153s IP in a browser and see it serving a page. (NOTE: Linode recommends a swap partition and not having one will prompt a warring on the Dashboard. Since we aren\226\128\153t using Linux I don\226\128\153t believe that is too much of a concern.) </p>\n\n<p>At this point you know as much as I do about how to get started with Mirage on Linode. I\226\128\153m still learning a bit about Jekyll and getting images working was my lesson for the day. I\226\128\153ll see about getting some sort of comment system up as I\226\128\153m sure there may be some questions about how to do this. </p>\n\n  </article>\n\n</div>\n\n      </div>\n    </div>\n\n    <footer class=\"site-footer\">\n\n  <div class=\"wrapper\">\n\n    <h2 class=\"footer-heading\">A Set Of Certain Musings</h2>\n\n    <div class=\"footer-col-wrapper\">\n      <div class=\"footer-col  footer-col-1\">\n        <ul class=\"contact-list\">\n          <li>A Set Of Certain Musings</li>\n          <li><a href=\"mailto:\"></a></li>\n        </ul>\n      </div>\n\n      <div class=\"footer-col  footer-col-2\">\n        <ul class=\"social-media-list\">\n          \n          <li>\n            <a href=\"https://github.com/CBothwell\">\n              <span class=\"icon  icon--github\">\n                <svg viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\">\n                  <path fill=\"#828282\" d=\"M7.999,0.431c-4.285,0-7.76,3.474-7.76,7.761 c0,3.428,2.223,6.337,5.307,7.363c0.388,0.071,0.53-0.168,0.53-0.374c0-0.184-0.007-0.672-0.01-1.32 c-2.159,0.469-2.614-1.04-2.614-1.04c-0.353-0.896-0.862-1.135-0.862-1.135c-0.705-0.481,0.053-0.472,0.053-0.472 c0.779,0.055,1.189,0.8,1.189,0.8c0.692,1.186,1.816,0.843,2.258,0.645c0.071-0.502,0.271-0.843,0.493-1.037 C4.86,11.425,3.049,10.76,3.049,7.786c0-0.847,0.302-1.54,0.799-2.082C3.768,5.507,3.501,4.718,3.924,3.65 c0,0,0.652-0.209,2.134,0.796C6.677,4.273,7.34,4.187,8,4.184c0.659,0.003,1.323,0.089,1.943,0.261 c1.482-1.004,2.132-0.796,2.132-0.796c0.423,1.068,0.157,1.857,0.077,2.054c0.497,0.542,0.798,1.235,0.798,2.082 c0,2.981-1.814,3.637-3.543,3.829c0.279,0.24,0.527,0.713,0.527,1.437c0,1.037-0.01,1.874-0.01,2.129 c0,0.208,0.14,0.449,0.534,0.373c"
let d_f33f66a376241d73b9860f753b7c4fa4 = "lass=\"language-bash\" data-lang=\"bash\"><span class=\"nv\">$ </span>env <span class=\"nv\">DHCP</span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"nb\">true </span>mirage configure --xen\n<span class=\"nv\">$ </span>make\n<span class=\"nv\">$ </span>make run</code></pre></div>\n\n<h3 id=\"basic-steps-first\">Basic steps first</h3>\n\n<p>I\226\128\153m not going to walk through buying an account or setting it up, it is pretty straight forward on how to do. Once you have the account set up head over to the <code>Linodes</code> tab and select the 1024 instance type. This is the single core 1024 GB node.</p>\n\n<p>If you already have a Linode you may be dropped into a selection screen for Linodes, just select the one you\226\128\153re going to put mirage on (in this case I\226\128\153ve labeled mine \226\128\152mirage\226\128\153). </p>\n\n<p><img src=\"/assets/linode-screenshot-1.png\" alt=\"linode-choices\" /></p>\n\n<p>You\226\128\153ll otherwise find your way onto the dashboard. From this screen we can set up our initial configuration. First we\226\128\153re going to create our disk image, for this step you\226\128\153ll want to click on the link <code>Create a new Disk Image</code>. You\226\128\153ll be provided a place to enter in some disk image information. We won\226\128\153t need a large disk image (remember we won\226\128\153t be installing Linux), so I\226\128\153ve elected to do about 1 GB with ext4 and labeled it <code>mirage-disk</code>. </p>\n\n<p><img src=\"/assets/mirage-disk-image.png\" alt=\"disk-image\" /></p>\n\n<p>From here we\226\128\153ll look up to the \226\128\152Dashboard\226\128\153 section of the Dashboard (I know :-( look at the image to see what I mean). We\226\128\153re going to click on the <code>Create a new Configuration Profile</code> link. </p>\n\n<p><img src=\"/assets/dashboard-configuration.png\" alt=\"dash-board-section\" /></p>\n\n<p>The next page has a large number of options on it, but there aren\226\128\153t really very many which we need to fill in. Run Level and Memory Limit can be left alone. I like to label things, because later on I\226\128\153ll forget what I was doing and so I\226\128\153d suggest you also label this configuration. The kernel needs to be pv-grub-x86_64 and we\226\128\153ll assign our single block device, the ext4 partition, to /dev/xvda (not the Finnix iso). Everything else can be left in the default state. Don\226\128\153t forget to save the changes at the bottom.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"/assets/configuration-profile.png\" alt=\"configuration-profile\" /></p>\n\n<h3 id=\"bowels-of-the-beast\">Bowels of the Beast</h3>\n\n<p>So far we\226\128\153ve just been manipulating the GUI to get the configuration that we want. Unfortunately, we\226\128\153re going to need to do some command line work to put this thing into action. </p>\n\n<p>In order to get the image onto the server we\226\128\153re going to rsync it to our disk image. To do that we would ordinarily need either access to the host or an environment which supported the other end of rsync and ssh (like another Linux distribution). </p>\n\n<p>As stated before, we\226\128\153re not going to install another Linux distribution here. Instead Linode provides a rescue environment they call lish and a rescue image called Finnix. To boot to Finnix we need to click on the <code>Rescue</code> tab and click on <code>Reboot into Rescue Mode</code>. </p>\n\n<p><img src=\"/assets/rescue-layer.png\" alt=\"rescue-layer\" /></p>\n\n<p>Once we click on <code>Reboot into Rescue Mode</code>, we\226\128\153ll be dropped back into the dashboard and the instance will begin starting up into rescue mode. Next we\226\128\153ll need to click on the <code>Remote Access</code> tab. </p>\n\n<p>This tab has some information on how to access the system remotely. In this instance we want to take a look toward the bottom of the page under the <code>Console Access</code> section where it says <code>Lish via ssh</code>. </p>\n\n<p>It will contain a line detailing how to ssh into the rescue layer (really lish, but since we\226\128\153ve started Finnix we\226\128\153ll be dropped into that). Copy and paste this line into your terminal. You\226\128\153ll be prompted for a password which will be the account password for Linode. </p>\n\n<p>From here there are only a few more steps we need to take to get our Mirage kernel working. We\226\128\153re going to need to mount the /dev/xvda disk image and add a"
