let d_3a45547a7cf6ba0e98f23e7f3ff3edc7 = "an>\n\n<span class=\"o\">...</span></code></pre></div>\n\n<p>The http server, S, serves files stored on the file system. You know, like a normal http server. This part appears to occur inside the <code>dispatcher</code> function. A list of strings is checked if it is empty or not. An empty list adds the <code>index.html</code> string to a list and calls dispatcher again\226\128\166so it isn\226\128\153t empty the second time. A non-empty path is assembled into a single string and the server tries to read the file from the file system. If it cannot find the file it returns my irreverent <code>Not found</code> error. </p>\n\n<div class=\"highlight\"><pre><code class=\"language-ocaml\" data-lang=\"ocaml\"><span class=\"c\">(* dispatch non-file URLs *)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">let</span> <span class=\"k\">rec</span> <span class=\"n\">dispatcher</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"k\">function</span>\n  <span class=\"o\">|</span> <span class=\"bp\">[]</span> <span class=\"o\">|</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"s2\">&quot;&quot;</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> <span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span> <span class=\"n\">dispatcher</span> <span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"s2\">&quot;index.html&quot;</span><span class=\"o\">]</span> \n  <span class=\"o\">|</span> <span class=\"n\">segments</span> <span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">let</span> <span class=\"n\">path</span> <span class=\"o\">=</span> <span class=\"nn\">String</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">concat</span> <span class=\"s2\">&quot;/&quot;</span> <span class=\"n\">segments</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span>\n    <span class=\"n\">try_lwt</span>\n      <span class=\"n\">read_fs</span> <span class=\"n\">path</span>\n      <span class=\"o\">&gt;&gt;=</span> <span class=\"k\">fun</span> <span class=\"n\">body</span> <span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span>\n      <span class=\"nn\">S</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">respond_string</span> <span class=\"o\">~</span><span class=\"n\">status</span><span class=\"o\">:`</span><span class=\"nc\">OK</span> <span class=\"o\">~</span><span class=\"n\">body</span> <span class=\"bp\">()</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> <span class=\"n\">exn</span> <span class=\"o\">-&gt;</span>\n      <span class=\"nn\">S</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">respond_not_found</span> <span class=\"bp\">()</span>\n<span class=\"k\">in</span></code></pre></div>\n\n<p><code>read_fs path</code> takes the path and passes it to the <code>read_fs</code> function where the file is looked up on the device. This is a <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZhuHCtR3xq8\">monad</a>, read_fs returns some string contained in an <code>Lwt.t</code>, so the <code>&gt;&gt;=</code> operator shoves whatever is returned by that <code>Lwt.t</code> into the variable <code>body</code> of the next function. Ocaml has labeled arguments (a nice feature for any language) and <code>~body</code> is short hand for <code>~body:body</code> (in case you were confused by that). </p>\n\n<p>Couple of things to note about the above code. I\226\128\153m not sure why this needs to be recursive. Not that recursion is a bad thing in Ocaml, but it just calls dispatcher at most twice with <code>[\"index.html\"]</code> in the list the second time. I suspect theres a more graceful way to deal with this (NOTE: my solution is probably not much better for this). Also and more importantly, it only serves the index.html page if and only if it is the root path. That is: it won\226\128\153t serve /about/index.html as /about/ like I want (and I guess Jekyll too). </p>\n\n<p>So now I need to find a way to change this code so it\226\128\153ll work for Jekyll. This shouldn\226\128\153t be too hard. I just need to find out how to determine if this path is actually a file or a directory. Next stop the <a href=\"http://mirage.github.io/\">Mirage Documentation</a>. </p>\n\n<h2 id=\"taking-a-wrong-turn\">Taking A Wrong Turn</h2>\n\n<p>Okay, there\226\128\153s a lot here and I\226\128\153m not sure what module I\226\128\153m using here for the file system. It makes sense to stat the file to see if it is a directory or not. I took a look higher up in the code to see what functions were being called on the FS module. </p>\n\n<div class=\"highlight\"><pre><co"
