let d_ab66482dd1405909f6c9e0afa626b59f = "n&gt;\n&lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Yep\226\128\166black magic. Looks like I\226\128\153m using &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/mirage/ocaml-crunch&quot;&gt;crunch&lt;/a&gt; and not the fat file system because that\226\128\153s the default. And I don\226\128\153t see a crunch module in the Ocaml documentation\226\128\166&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;When faced with a murky coding situation I fall back to my tried and true solution\226\128\166take a guess. I know it is the file system so something that operates on blocks or has \226\128\152-fs\226\128\153 at the end of it is a likely candidate. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;After some combing through the documentation, I located what looked like the package I wanted: &lt;a href=&quot;http://mirage.github.io/mirage/#Mirage_types.V1:FS.io&quot;&gt;Mirage_types.V1:FS.io&lt;/a&gt;. It has a &lt;code&gt;read&lt;/code&gt; function and a &lt;code&gt;size&lt;/code&gt; function that appears to match what I\226\128\153m using. Also, it has a &lt;code&gt;stat&lt;/code&gt; function which is what I need. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Unfortunately, after modifying the code to use the &lt;code&gt;stat&lt;/code&gt; function and removing the recursive part of dispatcher I received a compile time error when rebuilding. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-bash&quot; data-lang=&quot;bash&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;$ &lt;/span&gt;make\n...\nFile &lt;span class=&quot;s2&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;dispatch.ml&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;, line 41, characters 13-20:\nError: Unbound value FS.stat\nCommand exited with code 2.\nmake: *** &lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;main.native&lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; Error 10&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;h2 id=&quot;out-of-the-woods&quot;&gt;Out Of The Woods&lt;/h2&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;I\226\128\153m looking at the wrong module. One of these day\226\128\153s I\226\128\153ll need to get merlin working on my workstation. So I took another poke around the documentation. Actually it is using &lt;a href=&quot;http://mirage.github.io/mirage/#Mirage_types.V1:KV_RO&quot;&gt;Mirage_types.V1:KV_RO&lt;/a&gt; which makes more sense based on what the main module is using. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Even with the right module things aren\226\128\153t looking so great. There isn\226\128\153t a &lt;code&gt;stat&lt;/code&gt; function (actually the error told me that, but the documentation confirmed it). &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Eventually, I settled on a solution which catches the missing file error and then tries again by appending &lt;code&gt;index.html&lt;/code&gt; to the end of the path. This seems to work well, though I\226\128\153m not quite satisfied with using exceptions here. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-ocaml&quot; data-lang=&quot;ocaml&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;c&quot;&gt;(* dispatch non-file URLs *)&lt;/span&gt;\n&lt;span class=&quot;k&quot;&gt;let&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;dispatcher&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;segments&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; \n  &lt;span class=&quot;k&quot;&gt;let&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;path&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;nn&quot;&gt;String&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;p&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;concat&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;s2&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;/&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;segments&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;k&quot;&gt;in&lt;/span&gt; \n  &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;try_lwt&lt;/span&gt;\n    &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;read_fs&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;path&lt;/span&gt; \n    &lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;k&quot;&gt;fun&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;body&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;-&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt; \n    &lt;span class=&quot;nn&quot;&gt;S&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;p&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;n&quot;&gt;respond_string&lt;/span&gt; "
let d_1551afd7d4e18573982f41935709f86e = "<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n<rss version=\"2.0\" xmlns:atom=\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\">\n  <channel>\n    <title>A Set Of Certain Musings</title>\n    <description>A set of musings about coding, computers, and perhaps some other things...\n</description>\n    <link>http://christopherbothwell.com/</link>\n    <atom:link href=\"http://christopherbothwell.com/feed.xml\" rel=\"self\" type=\"application/rss+xml\"/>\n    <pubDate>Mon, 08 Dec 2014 12:44:22 -0600</pubDate>\n    <lastBuildDate>Mon, 08 Dec 2014 12:44:22 -0600</lastBuildDate>\n    <generator>Jekyll v2.5.2</generator>\n    \n      <item>\n        <title>Hello Linode</title>\n        <description>&lt;p&gt;It has been almost a week since my last post and I\226\128\153ve been working on getting this blog setup on a Xen virtual machine. Most folks seem to be setting up their mirage kernels on Amazon\226\128\153s EC2 instances or their private Xen cloud platforms. I thought it might be nice to try it out on a different public clould/Xen provider. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;h3 id=&quot;linode-and-mirage&quot;&gt;Linode and Mirage&lt;/h3&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;I haven\226\128\153t been able to find a walk through or tutorial on how to get Mirage set up on Lindoe. Linode provides a number of default Linux distributions which can be installed from a single within the control panel. However, like AWS, they provide a pv-grub instance which can be used to boot a custom distribution. The caveat is that there are quite a few more steps which need to be taken to get your Mirage kernel off the ground. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;The steps to getting this set up were pretty similar to the EC2 tutorial, however I encountered some major issues that were fixed by some minor tweaks of the steps. In the interest of time spent reading this post (also writing it) I won\226\128\153t go too much into what the specific problems were. Suffice to say the menu.lst needs to be a little bit different than what is shown for EC2 on the &lt;a href=&quot;http://openmirage.org/wiki/xen-boot&quot;&gt;Mirage tutorial&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Also, I haven\226\128\153t yet worked out how to automate the installation. I\226\128\153m pretty sure it can work similarly by installing a Linux distribution and then rsyncing in the kernel but I found that I could get the entire Mirage kernel installed on Linode without having to install a separate Linux distribution on the same node and I\226\128\153d like to keep that as a feature. Again, I haven\226\128\153t gotten the automation worked out yet, but it is coming. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;h3 id=&quot;getting-things-built-right&quot;&gt;Getting things built right&lt;/h3&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;When you build the unikernel you\226\128\153ll have several options on how to build in networking. Linode by default will use DHCP which can make life easy if you compile your Mirage unikernel with DHCP enabled. Like:&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-bash&quot; data-lang=&quot;bash&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;$ &lt;/span&gt;env &lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;DHCP&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;o&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;nb&quot;&gt;true &lt;/span&gt;mirage configure --xen\n&lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;$ &lt;/span&gt;make\n&lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;$ &lt;/span&gt;make run&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;h3 id=&quot;basic-steps-first&quot;&gt;Basic steps first&lt;/h3&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;I\226\128\153m not going to walk through buying an account or setting it up, it is pretty straight forward on how to do. Once you have the account set up head over to the &lt;code&gt;Linodes&lt;/code&gt; tab and select the 1024 instance type. This is the single core 1024 GB node.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;If you already have a Linode you may be dropped into a selection screen for Linodes, just select the one you\226\128\153re going to put mirage on (in t