let d_0456d61faa1d970d78ae70eec7a39cf7 = ". First we\226\128\153re going to create our disk image, for this step you\226\128\153ll want to click on the link &lt;code&gt;Create a new Disk Image&lt;/code&gt;. You\226\128\153ll be provided a place to enter in some disk image information. We won\226\128\153t need a large disk image (remember we won\226\128\153t be installing Linux), so I\226\128\153ve elected to do about 1 GB with ext4 and labeled it &lt;code&gt;mirage-disk&lt;/code&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/mirage-disk-image.png&quot; alt=&quot;disk-image&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;From here we\226\128\153ll look up to the \226\128\152Dashboard\226\128\153 section of the Dashboard (I know :-( look at the image to see what I mean). We\226\128\153re going to click on the &lt;code&gt;Create a new Configuration Profile&lt;/code&gt; link. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/dashboard-configuration.png&quot; alt=&quot;dash-board-section&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;The next page has a large number of options on it, but there aren\226\128\153t really very many which we need to fill in. Run Level and Memory Limit can be left alone. I like to label things, because later on I\226\128\153ll forget what I was doing and so I\226\128\153d suggest you also label this configuration. The kernel needs to be pv-grub-x86_64 and we\226\128\153ll assign our single block device, the ext4 partition, to /dev/xvda (not the Finnix iso). Everything else can be left in the default state. Don\226\128\153t forget to save the changes at the bottom.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/configuration-profile.png&quot; alt=&quot;configuration-profile&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;h3 id=&quot;bowels-of-the-beast&quot;&gt;Bowels of the Beast&lt;/h3&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;So far we\226\128\153ve just been manipulating the GUI to get the configuration that we want. Unfortunately, we\226\128\153re going to need to do some command line work to put this thing into action. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;In order to get the image onto the server we\226\128\153re going to rsync it to our disk image. To do that we would ordinarily need either access to the host or an environment which supported the other end of rsync and ssh (like another Linux distribution). &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;As stated before, we\226\128\153re not going to install another Linux distribution here. Instead Linode provides a rescue environment they call lish and a rescue image called Finnix. To boot to Finnix we need to click on the &lt;code&gt;Rescue&lt;/code&gt; tab and click on &lt;code&gt;Reboot into Rescue Mode&lt;/code&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;/assets/rescue-layer.png&quot; alt=&quot;rescue-layer&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;Once we click on &lt;code&gt;Reboot into Rescue Mode&lt;/code&gt;, we\226\128\153ll be dropped back into the dashboard and the instance will begin starting up into rescue mode. Next we\226\128\153ll need to click on the &lt;code&gt;Remote Access&lt;/code&gt; tab. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;This tab has some information on how to access the system remotely. In this instance we want to take a look toward the bottom of the page under the &lt;code&gt;Console Access&lt;/code&gt; section where it says &lt;code&gt;Lish via ssh&lt;/code&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;It will contain a line detailing how to ssh into the rescue layer (really lish, but since we\226\128\153ve started Finnix we\226\128\153ll be dropped into that). Copy and paste this line into your terminal. You\226\128\153ll be prompted for a password which will be the account password for Linode. &lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;From here there are only a few more steps we need to take to get our Mirage kernel working. We\226\128\153re going to need to mount the /dev/xvda disk image and add a few directories and files to it.&lt;/p&gt;\n\n&lt;div class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-bash&quot; data-lang=&quot;bash&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;$ &lt;/span&gt;mount /dev/xvda /media/\n&lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;$ &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;nb&quot;&gt;cd&lt;/span&gt; /media/ \n&lt;span class=&quot;nv&quot;&gt;$ &lt;/span&gt;mkdir -p boot/grub&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n\n&lt;p&gt;After making the boot and grub directories on /dev/xvda, we can then create the boot/grub/menu.lst file. It sho"
